If you are always tired, you can actually suffer from depression

Depression and chronic fatigue syndrome are two conditions that can make someone feel extremely tired, even after a good night's sleep.It is also easy to confuse feelings of fatigue with depression and vice versa.

Depression occurs when a person feels sad, anxious or hopeless for a long period of time.People who are depressed often have sleep problems.They can sleep too much or not sleep at all.

Chronic fatigue syndrome is a condition that causes a person to constantly feeling of fatigue without any fundamental cause.Sometimes chronic fatigue syndrome is mistakenly diagnosed as depression.

What are the differences between depression and fatigue?

The main difference between the two is that chronic fatigue syndrome is mainly a physical disorder while depression is a mental health disorder.There may be some overlap between the two.

Symptoms of depression may include:

• constant feelings of sadness, anxiety or voids;

• feelings of lack of hope, powerlessness or invalidity;

• disinterest in hobbies you once liked;

• cramps;

• stomach concerns;

• Other pain.

They can also have sleep problems, which can lead to exhaustion.

People with chronic fatigue syndrome often have physical symptoms that are usually not associated with depression.They include:

• joint pain;

• sensitive lymph nodes;

• Muscle pain;

•sore throat.

Depression and chronic fatigue syndrome also affect people different when it comes to their daily activities.People with depression often feel very tired and are not interested in doing any activity, regardless of task or how much effort is needed.Meanwhile, those with chronic fatigue syndrome usually want to engage in activities, but simply feel too tired to do so.

To diagnose each condition, your doctor will try to rule out other disorders that may cause similar symptoms.If your doctor thinks you have depression, he may refer to a mental health expert for evaluation.

An unfortunate connection

Unfortunately, people who have chronic fatigue syndrome can be depressed.And while depression does not cause chronic fatigue syndrome, it can certainly cause increased fatigue.

Many people with chronic fatigue syndrome have sleep disorders, such as insomnia or sleep apnea.These often exacerbate fatigue because they prevent people from resting well at night.When people feel tired, they may not have motivation or energy to perform their daily activities.Lack of desire to do something can risk them to develop depression.

